.TH "run\-one" "1" "April 22, 2026" "Version 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] \- a wrapper utility that prevents concurrent
execution of a command by ensuring only a single instance runs at any
given time
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.PP
\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \&...
COMMAND [\f[I]ARGS\f[R]] \&...
.SH DESCRIPTION
This utility prevents multiple instances of the same command from
running concurrently.
It can either block a new instance from starting if one is already
active (\f[B]run\-one\f[R]), or terminate the existing process and let
the new one take over (the \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] variant).
.PP
To ensure only one instance runs at a time, this utility uses a
flock\-based semaphore.
The unique ID for the lock is either specified on the command line using
the \f[B]\-T\f[R] parameter or generated automatically by hashing the
user command line.
The semaphore file is stored in one of the following directories in this
order of preference:
.IP
.EX
$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/one\-run
/run/user/$UID/one\-run
/dev/shm/one\-run_$UID
/tmp/one\-run_$UID
.EE
.PP
Most of these directories are on \f[B]tmpfs\f[R] file systems (/tmp is
often a \f[B]tmpfs\f[R] mount in many recent Linux distributions), and
all of them get cleaned up upon reboot.
.PP
The user supplied command line is then launched with a flock.
If the corresponding lock file is available, then the command gets
launched.
If the lock on the file was already acquired by another process then
depending on the flavor of command
(\f[B]run\-one\f[R]/\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R]) or use of option
\f[B]\-x\f[R], the utility either exits or attempts to terminate other
command instances, waiting for the lock to be released so that the user
command can be launched.
.PP
Wait time can be limited with \f[B]\-w\f[R].
In addition the other process can be terminated with \f[B]SIGKILL\f[R]
if it doesn\(cqt respond to \f[B]SIGTERM\f[R] in under the number of
seconds specified with \f[B]\-k\f[R].
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-x\f[R]
terminates other commands with the identical command ID (or command
signature) previously launched by \f[B]run\-one\f[R] or
\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R], locks the semaphore and runs this command;
equivalent to running \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-w SECONDS\f[R]
maximum time (in seconds) to wait for the lock to become available
before giving up on acquiring the lock; only whole numbers are
understood, decimals are not allowed
.TP
\f[B]\-k SECONDS\f[R]
(\f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R]) send \f[B]SIGKILL\f[R] to the other process
instance that holds the lock holder after this many seconds of waiting
for it to terminate gracefully with \f[B]SIGTERM\f[R]; only whole
numbers are understood, decimals are not allowed
.TP
\f[B]\-a\f[R]
run this invocation anyway, even if another process did not give up the
lock in the given wait time.
This invalidates the lock acquired by another process and creates a new
lock file
.TP
\f[B]\-T TOKEN\f[R]
use this token for the lock file name instead of calculating user
command hash.
This option is also used internally when running \f[B]keep\-one\-running
cmd\f[R], as this command variant internally runs as \f[B]run\-one +
keep\-running + cmd\f[R] but needs a hash token for \f[B]cmd\f[R] and
not \f[B]keep\-running + cmd\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-E EXIT_CODE\f[R]
custom error exit code; enables the user to differentiate between the
command failure and the utility exit error (see EXIT STATUS section for
details)
.TP
\f[B]\-D PATH\f[R]
debug/log file path
.TP
\f[B]\-h | \(enhelp\f[R]
Print help information
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
run\-this\-one inotifywait \-m \(ti/tmp \-e close_write | \(rs
    run\-until\-failure \-\- sh \-c \(aqread \-r event && echo \(dq$event\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
Sets a watcher on \(ti/tmp directory and keeps printing events that
occur whenever a new file is written in it.
If another identical instance of such watcher was already running, it
gets terminated prior to running this instance.
.IP
.EX
run\-one \-x \-T \-w 60 \-k 30 \(dqWatch my DIR\(dq inotifywait \-m \(ti/tmp \-e close_write | \(rs
    keep\-running \-u f \-r 100 \-\- sh \-c \(aqread \-r event && echo \(dq$event\(dq\(aq
.EE
.PP
This does the same as the previous example, except it matches the
command by the provided ID/token \(lqWatch my DIR\(rq, instead of
command signature.
This enables replacing this instance with an updated command later
e.g.\ if you decide to watch \f[B]/tmp\f[R] instead of
\f[B]\(ti/tmp\f[R].
It also limits the number of printed events to 100; it sends SIGKILL to
another process that holds the lock after 30 sec of waiting and quits
waiting altogether after 1 min.
.SH EXIT STATUS
\f[B]run\-one\f[R] and \f[B]run\-this\-one\f[R] exit with one of the
following status:
.IP
.EX
0     upon success
122   when this utility encounters a problem; customizable with \-E
.EE
.PP
Exit code 122 is returned the utility itself encounters an abnormal
situation, e.g.\ when a parameter is invalid of flock fails.
This code is customizable with \-E option.
.PP
Any other exit code indicates the status returned from the user command.
.SH SEE ALSO
